You’ve seen it. Hold down the side button for Siri, or press-and-hold in the Gemini app, and a soft rainbow glow blooms around the edges of the screen and slowly sweeps around. It’s a tiny detail, but it feels alive — and it’s the kind of polish that makes an app feel expensive.
I wanted that in a React Native app. I couldn’t find a drop-in that did exactly this — a glow that hugs the screen edges and follows the device’s real rounded corners — so I built one and published it as react-native-edge-glow.
This post is the story of building it: the approach that seemed obvious and failed, the one that worked, and the corner-radius problem that sent me into the Android platform APIs. If you just want to use it, skip to Using it at the bottom
The effect, broken into parts
A glow like this is really three things happening at once:

• A multi-color gradient wrapped around the screen border.

• That gradient sweeping around continuously.

• A soft bloom that fades inward from the edge to transparent.
And two constraints that make it interesting:

• It has to run at 60fps without stuttering — so the animation can’t live on the JS thread.

• It has to look right on both iOS and Android, whose screens have very different corners.
Attempt #1: the “obvious” way that fell apart
My first instinct was SVG masks and filters. Draw a big rainbow rectangle, mask it to a border shape, blur it with <FeGaussianBlur>, and rotate the whole thing to get the sweep. It worked beautifully… on iOS.
On Android it rendered nothing. A blank screen, no error.
It turns out SVG <Mask> and <Filter> support in react-native-svg is inconsistent across platforms — the exact combination I leaned on simply didn’t paint on Android. This is the sort of thing you only discover by testing on a real device on both platforms, which is a lesson worth internalizing: “it works on iOS” is half an answer.
So I threw it out and looked for a technique that used only primitives both platforms render identically.
Attempt #2: animate the gradient itself
Instead of rotating a masked, blurred shape, I animate the gradient’s coordinates.
A <LinearGradient> in SVG is defined by a start point (x1, y1) and an end point (x2, y2). If you slide those points diagonally across the screen over time, the colors appear to sweep around the border — no rotation math, no masks, no filters. Just four numbers changing.
// The gradient is painted onto the stroke of a rounded rect.
// Animating x1/y1/x2/y2 slides the colors around the edge.
<LinearGradient id="glow" x1="-60%" y1="140%" x2="40%" y2="240%">
<Stop offset="0%" stopColor="#8B5CF6" />
<Stop offset="50%" stopColor="#06B6D4" />
<Stop offset="100%" stopColor="#8B5CF6" />
</LinearGradient>Because the first and last color are the same, the loop is seamless — when the sweep wraps around, there’s no visible jump.
The bloom: no blur filter allowed
I still needed the soft glow that fades inward. SVG blur was off the table (see attempt #1), so I faked it with geometry.
The trick: draw the border as many concentric rounded rectangles, each one reaching a little deeper into the screen, all at a low opacity. Where they overlap — right at the edge — they stack up bright. As you move inward, fewer rings reach, so it fades to transparent. The composite is a gradient, built out of nothing but stroked rects.
// ~12 rings, each deeper and low-opacity; their overlap forms the fade.
{rings.map(r => (
<Rect
x={r.depth / 2} y={r.depth / 2}
width={W - r.depth} height={H - r.depth}
rx={cornerRadius} ry={cornerRadius}
stroke="url(#glow)" strokeWidth={r.depth}
strokeOpacity={0.07} fill="none"
/>
))}Keeping it off the JS thread
Animating those gradient coordinates every frame from JavaScript is a recipe for jank — every frame has to cross the bridge, and any hiccup in your JS thread (a fetch resolving, a re-render) shows up as a stutter in the glow.
Reanimated solves this. A shared value drives the animation on the UI thread, and useAnimatedProps feeds the animated coordinates straight into the SVG gradient without touching JS per frame:
const progress = useSharedValue(0);
useEffect(() => {
progress.value = withRepeat(
withTiming(1, { duration: 2600, easing: Easing.linear }),
-1, // forever
false,
);
}, []);
const gradientProps = useAnimatedProps(() => {
'worklet';
const p = progress.value;
return {
x1: `${-60 + p * 200}%`,
y1: `${140 - p * 200}%`,
x2: `${40 + p * 200}%`,
y2: `${240 - p * 200}%`,
};
});Now the glow keeps sweeping smoothly even while your app is busy doing real work. Measured on a mid-range device it holds ~60fps with the JS thread completely idle between frames.
The rabbit hole: what corner radius?
Here’s the part I didn’t expect to spend an evening on.
The glow is drawn on a rounded rectangle. What radius? If I guess too small, the glow cuts across a rounded iPhone corner. Too big on a squared-off Android phone, and it bulges past the screen. Every device is different.
iOS. There is no public API for the display’s corner radius. Apple just doesn’t expose it. So iOS gets a fixed, hand-tuned approximation (~55pt) that matches modern iPhones well enough. (There’s a private _displayCornerRadius KVC trick, but shipping private API is an App Store risk I wasn’t willing to take on other people’s behalf.)
Android. This is the fun bit. Since Android 12 (API 31), there’s a public, documented API that reports the physical corner radius of the display: WindowInsets.getRoundedCorner(). Most people have never heard of it. So I wrote a tiny native module that reads it:
val insets = decorView.rootWindowInsets
val radiusPx = insets
?.getRoundedCorner(RoundedCorner.POSITION_TOP_LEFT)
?.radius ?: 0
promise.resolve(radiusPx / density) // -> dpOn my Pixel emulator this returned 30.33dp — the real, physical curvature of that screen. The glow now traces the actual corner instead of guessing. On devices below API 31 (or genuinely square screens) it reports 0 and the glow falls back to square corners, which is correct.
That’s the difference between an effect that looks bolted on and one that looks native: it matches the hardware.
Presets, pulse, and accessibility
Once the core worked, the rest was ergonomics:

• Presets — rainbow, siri, gemini, aurora, sunset — so you don’t have to hand-pick colors.

• A breathing pulse that gently fades the whole glow in and out (very Siri), togglable and tunable.

• Reduce Motion support — if the OS accessibility setting is on, the glow holds still instead of animating. Free respect for users who need it.
Using it
npm install react-native-edge-glow react-native-svg react-native-reanimatedRender it as the last child of a full-screen container — it positions itself absolutely and ignores touches:
import { useState } from 'react';
import { Pressable } from 'react-native';
import EdgeGlow from 'react-native-edge-glow';
function Screen() {
const [holding, setHolding] = useState(false);
return (
<Pressable
style={{ flex: 1 }}
onPressIn={() => setHolding(true)}
onPressOut={() => setHolding(false)}
>
{/* your content */}
<EdgeGlow active={holding} preset="siri" />
</Pressable>
);
}That’s it. Colors, sweep speed, glow width, pulse, corner radius — all props, all documented in the README.
The honest part: know its limits
I’ll be straight about the tradeoff. Because the gradient coordinates change every frame, the SVG is re-rasterized on the CPU each frame. For a press-and-hold effect that runs for a few seconds, that’s completely smooth and totally fine. If you need a glow running continuously for minutes, glowing around arbitrary components, or targeting very low-end hardware, you want GPU rendering instead — reach for react-native-animated-glow, which is Skia-based and built for exactly that. Different tools for different jobs; I’d rather point you to the right one than pretend mine does everything.
Wrapping up
What started as “I want that Siri glow” turned into a nice little tour: why SVG filters aren’t portable, how to fake a bloom with geometry, how to keep animation off the JS thread, and a genuinely useful Android API almost nobody uses.
If you build something with it, I’d love to see it.

